Sure thing. Here’s a simple **CSS/stylesheet guide** you can drop into any Markdown renderer that supports custom styling (e.g., docs site, Notion, MkDocs, or static‑HTML export).  
It keeps everything legible in both light and dark themes and preserves that calm, professional look:

```css
/* ===== Crisis‑Response Quick Reference Styles ===== */

/* Base font and sizing */
body {
  font-family: "Source Sans Pro", Arial, sans-serif;
  font-size: 15px;
  line-height: 1.55;
  color: var(--text, #222);
  background-color: var(--bg, #fff);
  margin: 2em;
}

/* Headings */
h1, h2, h3 {
  font-weight: 600;
  color: #143b5d;           /* calm blue tone */
  margin-top: 1.5em;
  margin-bottom: 0.4em;
}

/* Table formatting */
table {
  width: 100%;
  border-collapse: collapse;
  margin: 1em 0;
}

th, td {
  border: 1px solid #ddd;
  padding: 0.6em 0.8em;
  vertical-align: top;
}

th {
  background-color: #e7f1f8; /* pale blue header */
  font-weight: 600;
}

tr:nth-child(even) {
  background-color: #f8fbfd;
}

/* Code blocks for sample scripts */
code, pre {
  background-color: #f3f3f3;
  border-radius: 4px;
  padding: 2px 6px;
  font-size: 0.95em;
}

/* Blockquote for footers or hotline text */
blockquote {
  border-left: 4px solid #6ba4cf;
  padding-left: 1em;
  color: #333;
  font-style: italic;
}

/* Footer section */
footer {
  margin-top: 2em;
  font-size: 0.9em;
  color: #555;
}

/* Dark‑mode override */
@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
  body { 
    --bg: #1d1f21; 
    --text: #eee; 
    color: var(--text);
    background-color: var(--bg);
  }
  th { background-color: #2b3a47; }
  tr:nth-child(even) { background-color: #242b33; }
  blockquote { border-color: #4d8ecf; color: #ddd; }
}
```

**Usage**
1. Paste this CSS into your documentation theme or alongside your Markdown file.
2. Link it in your renderer (e.g., `<link rel="stylesheet" href="crisis‑lang.css">`).
3. The colors and type are intentionally neutral, printable, and WCAG‑friendly.

